annotation: Here's a kingside attack that actually worked!  My games recently have been littered with the other sort hence my plummeting rating.
I revert to an old favourite not actually considered a cutting edge response to the Najdorf these days.

I play this in order that if Black advances his d-pawn I don't have to attend immediately to the bishop's safety.  From b3 it still drills through to f7 traditionally Black's weak point on the kingside.
This is more aggressive than and statistically slightly superior to 8. 0-0 if my memory serves me correctly.
White hastens to attack while Black's king is still in the centre.
The natural response counter-attacking White's central knight but leaving a slight hole at d5.

From here the N can move to c3 to support the other N when it has gone to d5.  Alternatively it can go to g3 to defend e4 and potentially go via h5 to g7 or f6.  These options seem more flexible than those arising from 10. Nf3.
Black occupies White's weakest diagonal preventing castling.
So White harasses the enemy queen immediately.
The check has helped White to develop his remaining minor piece.
At last White can castle.  The main advantage of this manoeuvre is to develop the rook as the king doesn't look much safer on g1 than on e1 given that gaping diagonal.
The N was controlling b6 and c5 so Black's pawn thrust is very pertinent especially as the QB can now develop to b7.
Black opens up his castling options developing his final minor piece.
Before launching an attack White puts his king on a less exposed square.  I'd be interested in opinions as to whether this move in this position is a necessary prophylactic move or a waste of tempo.

Black makes his choice.  Now White knows where to concentrate his fire.  His pieces are reasonably well placed for action on either wing at this point but the bishops exploit their long range potential in the direction of the kingside.  So a kingside attack it is...

First White shifts the QR to c1 to oppose the enemy Queen and support the c-pawn in the event its other defenders desert it.  Possibly another wasted move or proper completion of development before undertaking decisive action?
This N appears to be heading for c4 or supporting an advance to d5.
The first aggressive gesture on the kingside aimed at removing a key defender the Nf6.
Black seizes the abandoned e-pawn.
Black is a pawn up and has a powerful looking central bishop.  In return White nearly has control of f6 and an attack on g7.
White threatens mate in 1.
The threat has provoked a weakness in Black's defensive position.
An interesting choice.  The other option was 21. f6 after which White has to single-mindedly manoeuvre his Q via g5 and h6 to g7 to deliver mate.  Black has to prevent the manoeuvre at all costs.
Black's powerful bishop assumes the role of a pawn.
White's QB attacks the defending rook and the g7 square.

Now f7 falls.  The B on g6 cannot recapture because of the pin by the Q.  Te K can't capture because of the Rf1.  All White's pieces except his QR are involved in the attack and mate is inevitable: 23....Kh8 24. Bg7++
This was the starting position in the Colle-Zuckertort match.
This move seems good. Bringing the knight in to the game is possibly slightly better than the alternative moves which to my mind would be the highly aggressive 8. Ne5 or the docile 8. a3.
Putting pressure on the most critical diagonal and at also down the vulnerable c-file.
Opening up seemed the only way forward.
Stopping this move would have been the main point of an early 8. a3 from white. I really hoped Muff would let me trade with his bishop.
... but understandably he had other plans for his bishop!
Less sure about this. I did not really like the center-controlling pawns but I found nothing better to do.
I had to get away from pawn onslaught somehow! (... Be7 is of coures an alternative but it looks more passive)
A slight loss of self esteem for my knight.
The bishop might have been a valuable resource but this knight was just too annoying!
The knight makes another attempt ... may be wiser this time. The there is a double threat in this move: (1) the pawn on c4 is hanging and (2) there is the nice fork on b3.
The pawn decoy worked!
The knight happily trades its life for the life of a rook!
To protect the knight. Otherwise 19. Ng4 would be crushing (given the mate threat on h7).
Protecting from the nest.
The only option here. Kh1 would have lost the knight due to d5 and Ng4.
I can resist anything ... except temptations!
This is a truly brilliant move which I had missed completely! It immediately puts my poor pinned knight in danger and I cannot even get out of the pin!
I thought long about what to do ... and then I found d4!
This surprised me as it would let me take the white knight. The idea behind d4 was "you pin me I pin you". That is if Muff took with the bishop I would slide my rook over to d8!
g5+! Now I faced another tough decision whether to take or not to take. And then of course ...
... I take!
Good move!
? e2 was possibly better.
In hindsight this was a mistake. Qg4 was possibly better.
I thought my king was rather safe at this point ...
... which I now doubted. Another brilliant move from my opponent. Take or not to take? ...
... as usual take!
... alternatively h3.
Threatening checkmate on g5!
I was now up 8 points and thought I could ward off the death treat from behind. This move was probably my biggest mistake yet!
37. Bxf5!! Taking with the rook would not have been good in fact quite bad for black!
Brilliant move! Rather than taking my knight as I was sure he would do my opponent put up annother death threat! This time on h6.
The only possible response.
hxg5! The right choice! Now there is a yet a new mate threat. This time by Qh2. When pressured like this there is only one gentlemany thing to do ...
... to sacrifice his queen! (There is no other way to get out of the check mate threat).

At this point rather ironically we reached material equality! But as there was no way ahead to ward of future checkmates I resigned! I am thankful to my brilliant opponent for an amazing game - a victory well deserved!
c3?  Perhaps d3 or d4 so your bishop is not blocked and your knight can take c3
b3?  Now you could have move d4 and attacked the centre.
good you got to d4
Why retreat?  You have my knight frozen against the queen.
I'm not sure why you sacrificed your biship here.  Was this part of a plan?

Your bishop may have been better off on e3.  You have a potential discovered attack on a7 by moving the knight off of d4.  If you could get your queen to a4 (move b3 to b4) you have a possible checkmate with Qa7.

I think you were getting tired here.  This should work but then on your next move you take with the pawn rather than the other knight.  I think your plan was with the knight rather than opening up your king.
This is the beginning of the fall once you start opening up your king.  Things really started to unravel here.
This is an oops.
Forgot about your rook.
Are you protecting your queen?  Don't forget about your king.
Desperation or just an oversight?
This is good for me since I am so far ahead now I don't mind exchanging pieces.  This was your only other attacking piece.
And now there were none.  It is really over here since you have no attacking pieces.  A stalement is always a possiblity though.
e4 is a useful openning for using bishop and quenn.
And this move does not give you any advantages. Actually it stops your upgrading.
Center of the board is going to be mine... This is a big advantage.
As you see i am moved my pieces to center. But opponent could not yet.
This is a small move. But after this move you can win the game easily. Because as i said at start: if you dont upgrade your pieces that means you have not pieces...
hes to take it.

Now if black plays 6- ... Ke8 7- Qh5+ g6 8- Qxg6#... 
İf he plays 
Than black plays 6-... Kf6 7- Qf3+ Ke6 8- Qf5+ Kd6 9- Nc4+ Kc6 10- Qd5#
But he played  Ke6... still no chance...
Because he lost his queen at start of game.. Than he resigned..
Scotch game considered fairly moribund until revivified somewhat late last century by Harry Kasparov.
The most usual and probably best response.
This inaugurates the Scotch Game.  If White is more adventurous he can try various gambits (Scotch Goring) by 4.Bc4 or 4.c3.  Both lead to interesting play.
Black's range of options here is huge.  One possibility a sometime favorite of W. Steinitz is 4...Qh4.  I've tried it myself on GK though on the second occasion it got me into some hot water...
An automatic response you might think but in fact much more frequently played is 5...Qf6 threatening a mate on f2.  White usually responds with 6.Qf3 whereat Black takes 6...bxc6.
Instead 6...Qh4 has been tried a number of times... with indifferent success...
Better than pushing the pawn to e5 I think.
(!?) Completing the mobilisation of the minor pieces.  More usual here is 8.0-0 probably because it is safer.

(!) Attacking the centre before White's King can depart the scene.  Probably White ought to castle out of trouble right now: 9.0-0 Nxe4 10.Nxe4 Rxe4 11.Bxf7! (Desperado!) 11...Kxf7 12.Qf3 Rxf4 (White was threatening 13.Bxc7+) 13.Qxf4+ Kg6 (Not 13...Kg8 14.Qc4+ picking up the bishop).  White would have had work to do to survive with a rook for 2 bishops but his prettier pawns will have been a help.  Possibly White could enquire after a draw by 14.Qg3+ with the idea 14...Qg5 15.Qxc7.
(!) Very strong.  Black is about to smash open the centre.  White is in trouble...

(??) ... and this move ought to have been fatal.  Probably best is to cover up by 10.e5 and hang on.  The pin on the e-pawn would be matched (more or less) by the one on Black's d-pawn.   Although not as effective as the bishop move even 10.0-0-0 is better than the text though 10...Bg4 would have been very nasty.
(?!) Not the best as it happens.  10...Bg4 would just about have been curtains.  Now White gets a reprieve...

(?) I think James must have overlooked the fact that after 11.Rxd8 the e8-rook would have been (half-)pinned and could have been exchanged off.  After 11.Rxd8! exf3+ 12.Rxe8+ Nxe8 13.gxf3 Nd6 the game would have been near on even. Now Black wins a piece...

(?) That Black has an immediately decisive continuation here is not easy to spot as the move he does play (12...Qxd1+) seems so obvious and it gives Black a big advantage as well.  Objectively best was 12.Be2 accepting the loss of a minor piece.  But Savielly Tartakover once observed with hard-headed acuity: 'Sometimes the second-best move is better than the best move!'
(!?) Black could have forced White's capitulation with 12...Bxf2+! 13.Ke2 Bg4+! winning White's Q whilst saving his own.

Mobilising his rook and apparently pinning the knight against the empty e8-square.  Unfortunately Black's knight is not pinned.  Of the two options available (...Nd6; and ...Nxf2+) Black chooses the more aggressive...
Possibly more circumspect was 15...Bd6 but this move contains some interesting surprises.
As you would expect.  Doesn't this rook fork win one of the bishops and restore the material balance?
(?) Bringing the game back to near-equality.  With 16....Rd8! and the threat on mate on d1 Black would enabled himself to keep his extra piece e.g.: 16...Rd8 17.Be2 Rd5!
Probably the better of the two captures available.
Slightly better might have been 17...Be4.
Of course not 18.Bxd3??
With the clear intention of exchanging off the minor pieces...
Rather risky.  Black could now have been a real nuisance and played 20...Ne1.  Mind you White might have been equally obdurate and tried 21.Kc1 in response: 'Care to repeat moves?'
But Black's not interested in such finesses...
This rook ending although Black has an extra pawn is well-nigh even.  Black's split pawns on the Q-side somewhat depreciate his extra pawn on the other wing.

(!?) A little dubious I feel.  White could just about have forced a draw at this or the previous move by attacking the c- and a-pawns: 23.Rc4 Rc8 24.Ra4 Ra8 etc. Now the rook's access to the Q-side is blocked and King has almost lost touch with his own pawns...

Right idea but the rook ought to have moved one further square.  Possibly Black fancying his chances with an extra pawn in aa pawn ending was hoping that White would offer a rook exchange by 24.Rd4...

(?!) Better was 24.Kc3 keeping the enemy rook out of the second rank.  But White could also have contemplated going into the pawn ending after 24.Rd4! Rxd4!? 25.Kxd4 - a very interesting line of play.  For instance 25...f5 26.Ke5 h6 27.h4! looks very favorable for White.
(?) Too passive.  24...Rd2 was indicated and Black would have had a distinct edge.
It was not too late for ...Rd2.
(!) Well played!  Surely Black dare not accept this exchange offer?
Overestimating his chances in the ensuing endgame - though it is easy to suppose Black is fine here.  After all the recapture lures the White King away from the Q-side where Black is weakest...
(!?) Possibly already Black ought to have been looking to counterattck on the K-side - advancing his pawns...

(!) A nice little finesse.  In this instance 28.Kd5 would seem just as good and indeed it is.  Black will respond 28...Ke7.  But in moving at once to the c-file White offers Black the opportunity to move 28...Ke6? instead whereat 29.Kc6 grabs the 'Opposition' and an extra tempo.
Black doesn't buy it (nor was there any reason that he should).

(!?) Launching his counterattack at last.  In ordinary circumstances one might have been inclined to play the 'candidate' pawn first: ...f5.  But Black is hoping to accelerate the process by inducing a weakness in White's K-side.  Had White's attack on the other wing been less well advanced this would have been a very good plan.

(!?) Sufficient.  But I would seriously have considered playing 31.a4 first. Then supposing Black were to play 31...h4 continued like this 32.a5! ... (one would like to play 32.b5 here but 32...a5 spoils the party) 32...h3  33.g3 f5 34.b5 etc.
Also good was 32.Kb7

Diabolical cunning.  White might have been tempted to try and lame Blacks K-side by 34.g4 - normally a good policy.  But here Black would have come storming back: 34.g4? f5! 35.gxf5 g4! and suddenly Black's counterattack is looking more than merely dangerous...

(!) Not to be deflected.  In the last few moves Black might have tried ...Kc8 but Ka7 would have been good enough for White to win.  His pawns would have won the race easily enough: the advantage of a 2-1 majority over a 3-2...
White is clearly winning now.  He could also have exchanged first on f4 (and 36.gxf4 g4 held no terrors for White) but White was sticking to a predetermined plan.
Nor would 38...Kd7 have saved the h-pawns: 38...Kd7 39.Qc8+ K-any 40.Qxc7+ ... 41.Qxh2.

An alternative plan was to use this Queen to stymie the pawns (40.Qh1 g3) and shove the other pawn home.  But the plan White has adopted by this move is very precise.  Black is being offered not a shred of counterplay.
Black tosses in the sponge.  1-0.

Hi everyone!

This is my return game with Coach Ion as black in the King's Indian 4 Pawns Attack.  In this game I achieved only my second High Draw against him.  Between the two draws I have had some really bad games including the King's Indian 4 Pawns Attack as White in which I blundered a piece after walking into a pin and never recovered.  Also that game Pipped at the Post was only a pretence of a contest although Ion got his checkmate in first I was never really in that game.  Then there was this shocker - I think Be6 was the loser - I followed the database and I think that that move should be given the skull and crossbones http://gameknot.com/analyze-board.pl?bd=13392792&fb=1&rnd=0.7322375019235583 - do you the Jury agree on that one?  Anyhow I will take you to move 6 in this game ......
6. ...... c5 - a first attempt at breaching the wall after some standard King's Indian 4 Pawn Attack moves.
7. ...... e6 - attempt No.2.
9. cxd5 - pawn trade.
12. fxe5 - now only 2 pawns are left after the breach in the wall.
13. ..... Ne5 - handy how my horsie can jump on a good square where he does not have to worry about pawn molestation!
14. ...... Rxf7 - another pawn trade - only 1 pawn standing but ssss it is a passer!
15. .... Nbd7 - out comes my other knight to support my king knight and to clear the decks on that back row!
18. ...... Qf8 - a lot has been going on over the last few moves one pair of minor pieces has been traded and I now offer a queen trade.  Ion chooses to put his bishop in the way.

19. ..... Qf5 - puts Glenda in a more active spot with ideas of Qc2.  I also have Rf8 in mind but I got impatient and played Be5 first.  Maybe I should have played Rf8 and traded off all the major pieces after all Henry is closer to that d5 pawn that Ion's king.
22. Rxf3 - the queens have been traded off and now I must take Ion's bishop to avoid remaining a piece down.
23. ..... Rf8 - the knight on e5 is temporarily protected by the rook on f8.  Ion is more than welcome to take the knight because if he does he will lose his king!
24. Kg1 - naturally evading Old Matey's shadow by moving his king towards the centre now that we are in an endgame.

24. ...... Nd7 - here this steed remains for the rest of the game.  I bet you are all  wondering how on earth do I avoid losing this one when I am playing effectively a piece down against such a strong Expert?

25. d6 - that passer advances only my steed stands between the pawn on d6 and promotion.  Thankfully that is as far as that pawn ever gets.  I did think Ion would play Re7 but then I can play Rf7 because Henry can recapture towards the passed pawn and if I get checked on the back rank back goes my rook.
27. Re2 - Ion eschews the trade because he does not want Henry to consume a p(r)awn cracker for his supper (that p(r)awn on d6 is particularly juicy - truly fit for a king!)
29. ..... a6 - I do not wish Ion's horsie to hop onto b5.
30. ..... Re5 - keeping my rook as active as I can.
32. ...... h5 - trying to hold back g4.
34. ...... Kg7 - now Henry must enter the fray!
36. ..... Rf7 - my rook retreats to a safe square.
37. Ng5 - I anticipated this move but never mind my rook can go to f6 and if Ion puts his knight back on e4 then I can always put my rook back on f7 and do this dance again!
38. ..... Kh6 - Henry bravely steps onto the h column to put the question to Ion's horsie which shies off to e4.
39. ..... Rf8 - rather a passive square but I am thinking about protecting the back row just in case my knight is compelled to move away from d7.
40. ...... Re8 - Ion's last rook move to d5 has permitted my own rook to move off the f file for now thanks to my pawn on g6.  I now decide to pin that pesky knight.
42. ...... Rf8 - back goes my rook onto the f column to avoid letting Ion take control of the f column.  Should Ion put his rook on the h column my rook is also gonna go there.
43. Nc3 - a retreat does Ion have something up his sleeve?
43. ..... Rf5 - my rook assumes a relatively active position and attacks Ion's isolani on g5.  It feels good when I can combine attack with defense.

44. Rd5! - Ion knows just how much I lurve exchanges.  Luckily I smell a rat.  If Rxd5 then 45. Nxd5 Kf7 46. Kd5 Ke6 and now 47. Nf4+.  Either Henry must defend the pawn on g6 allowing Ion's king to make a decisive penetration on my queenside or I must take the d6 pawn and allow a passer on the g column.  Either way I will be letting Ion's king become a bull in a china shop on my queenside.  So I play the seemingly passive Rf8 and hold out the olive branch.  I half expected a refusal given the rating differential and the fact that I have played badly against him in the matches between the two draws against him.  Ion did not refuse and so at least I only had to wait five matches before getting my second draw against him - the first one took 14 games to achieve so maybe some encouraging signs are just around the corner as I strive to regain my Class A status.  Well I will worry about that later and toast the here and the now!

44. ..... Rf8 - Ion you played really well and you did nothing wrong.  I think though that I have been threatening to do this to you and Master Freddy for a long long time but not quite succeeded.  Thankfully I allowed no silly tactics in this game and so I gave you nothing and you had to settle for a Low Draw.  Better luck next time - Joanne.

Hi everyone!

This is the third game in the sacrifices theme.  This is a team game.  I got paired up against an opponent nearly 40 points north of my rating.  All seemed lost in the middlegame when I blundered a pawn due to a tactical oversight.  I think this is the only the second time on gameknot I have blundered a pawn to a higher rated opponent and lived to tell the tale the other was my first ever Master Draw.  So how did all this happen well read on.
1. ...... d5 - in response to e4 Jiri plays d5 which is the Centre Counter or the Scandinavian Defense.

3. ..... Nxd5 - sometimes the advanced d pawn drops off directly with Qxd5 but then the queen can be a target in the centre in the opening.  However it is playable and the queen usually lands on a5.  Jiri decided that it was more prudent to develop a knight.
4. ..... Bg4 - the pieces are coming out quickly.
8. c4 - a strike at the knight on d5 now where is that steed going?
9. Nc3 - that knight went to b6.  Now I develop my queen knight to his usual square.
10. Be3 - development is complete.
11. b3 - to support my pawn on c4.
12. Qd2 - both queens move off the back row to connect our respective rooks.
13. ...... Bb4 - a nasty looking pin.  Suddenly my d4 pawn is looking a little vulnerable.
16. Qb2 - Glenda sidesteps the pin.  I must be careful of my loose bishop on h5 though.
19. Qb2?? - Glenda what have you done I think you should have moved to d2 instead.  Now I lose a pawn.
20. fxe3 - after the N for B trade Fou Leblanc and a pawn on e3 will be attacked by the Wicked Witch next move and so I must yield my e3 pawn.
21. Bf3 - best - you will see how in a minute.

25. Bxb7 - a lot has happened over the past 4 moves.  Firstly the queens have been traded and now one pair of rooks.  Fou Leblanc now busts up Jiri's queenside but I must worry about that 4 - 2 kingside majority that Jiri has.  He already has a passer on the e column.
27. Rd2 - if only I can prize that pesky horsie off the d column.
29. Kf2 - Henry must assist in trying to contain those kingside pawns.
29. ....... g5 - which just keep rolling along.
30. ....... e4?! - here is where black starts to go a little awry I now have an opportunity to rid myself of that knight even though I will have to trade in Fou Leblanc to do it.
31. Rd2 - now if Rd8? protecting the knight then Ke3 will win back a pawn if f4+.  So he moves the knight to b5.
32. ...... cxb5 - I have got rid of the knight and now my rook has a whole open d column to control.  Although I remain a pawn to the bad my position has improved and I have a passer on c5 to boot.
33. b4 - and I support the passer with b4.
33. ..... Kg7?! - here is the speculative sac - returning a pawn.  He wants to get his king into play but he will have to return a pawn.

34. ...... Kf6 - note if Rf7?? then 35. c6! followed by Rxf7 and then Glenda will appear on c8.  If the rook takes on d7 on move 35 then the pawn recaptures and Glenda appears next move on d8.  Jiri does not fall into this trap and wisely advances his king to f6.
35. Rxa7 - I was spoilt for choice but I decided to counter with a 3-1 majority on the queenside.  Was the alternative capture better?  You the jury decide.
36. Ke2 - Henry must stop Rd2+.
38. Rxa4 - I now have two connected passed pawns on the b and c column but what will the BR and the BK do?  I'm about to find out.

38. ...... Rc8 - this move holds up the c pawn quite nicely.  If the black king were on g6 and not f6 I may well have had this game in the bag.  My rook must now use up a couple of tempi to protect the passers from the rear - always the best place for your rook when you have passed pawns - defend from behind and not from in front or the side.  Rooks need three things mobility mobility and mobility!
40. ...... Kd5 - my pawns can go no further but can Jiri's?

42. ..... hxg4 - at least the three to one majority on the kingside is close enough for Henry to contain.  Note that if Jiri's king moves onto the fourth rank or one square away from my c pawn it will advance!

43. Ke3 - and draw offer.  I did not think that either side could make progress with our respective pawns.  My opponent agreed and accepted the draw offer so I came out of this with a High Draw and one rating point wheew!  Do you think that Jiri's return pawn sacrifice was sound or do you have any other alternatives for him.  You the Inquest Jury decide.

Setting up his bishop on g7 square is what it seems. Moved h3 to avoid the Bg4 and also for him to release his knight so he cant trap my queen side rook.

Avoiding the pressure from Bobotsov's QB which will be fianchettoed.
Portisch has a slight lead in development.
If Bobotsev accepts the sacrifice Portisch can put him under tremendous pressure.
Taking the plunge.
Pinning the Bishop. Now Portisch's advantage in development is turned to account.
A mistake. Bobotsev should unpin the Bishop at once.
One move too late.
Ripping open the King-side.
KxN is met with Q-N4ch and the King-hunt would be on in earnest.
Portisch tightens the screws.
Bobotsov is a Pawn down with a shattered position. He fights on for a short while longer.

This is considered an inaccuracy although I did not play the appropriate moves to take advantage. Generally White should play 4. a3 Bxc3 or 4. Qa4+ Nc6 which both give White a strong game.
The book considers Bxc3+ generally not such a great idea because White fairly easily undoubles the pawns and often ends up with the Bishop pair
This move puzzled me. It seems to block of the Kingside Knight and weaken that side of board in general
I probably should have played 6. cxd5 to undouble the pawns immediately
This wastes a Bishop move which could have been avoided with cxd5 earlier
Blocking off the other knight from easy development
With my light squared Bishop and Queen on the board Black's king seem awfully exposed to attack after the castle
My opponent overlooks the natural attack
I'm just trying to get pieces out now and find an attack later

Really the only place to develop the Knight although I thought offering a Queen trade with 13. ... Qd7 14. Qxd7 Nxd7 wasn't bad for Black at all although White isn't forced to trade and probably should not
I'm looking at pushing the e-pawn and probably the f-pawn to make an attack
This prevents 15. ... Nf4 threatening the Queen and then 16. ... Ne2+
Clearing the path for the f-pawn if needed and getting rid of the pesky defender
I'm not sure this was a useful move. Perhaps 17. ... c5 18. d5 Qa5 is better
My opponent gave me an opportunity with 17. ... Qd6 and so I played this instead of pushing the f-pawn

Ferrying more pieces into the attack. His kingside is in big trouble he only has one active defender and all my pieces are on the way to attack.

The "slow" way to start the game. I'm rather partial to the other central pawn thrust mainly because it can lead to an overwhelming position in a very short span of time if only one move isn't accurate.
I guess the only reason to still play 1...d5 is to reach the QGA as Black which isn't such a bad deal provided you're willing to suffer through the middlegame.
The other "slow" move. White seizes the d5 square but does nothing for his development.

Black prepares to fianchetto the Bishop. If I'd had to chose between this and 2...e6 in terms of objective strength I'd go with the the latter but in matter of preference I'm going to stick with this one.
Finally White develops a piece. But he's still a long way from castling.
Relinquishing control of e4 Black speeds up development and postpones the central struggle.
The whole point behind White's move order to control the center with pawns. Stenitz would have been appalled at Black's play but dogmas have a short lifespan in chess.
Preventing an early e5 and preparing for a central pawn push.
Not having chosen a specific line against the KID I decided to go with the 4-pawn attack and see how it turns out.
Black castles and is ready to hit the center.
White really needs to complete development and secure the King.
The classic way to meet White's central pawn mass.
After this the games moves towards a Benoni structure.

Black wants to open the e-file to pressurize the e-pawn. This approach is highly risky because if Black lets his guard down and allows White to play e5 he'll have a very hard time coordinating his pieces.
Closing the e-file and preparing to castle.
The typical pawn exchange. Black wants to use Q-side pawns to achieve counterplay and secure a balanced game.
The symmetrical recapture doesn't promise White anything.
I think 9...Re8 would have been stronger here but this Bishop is notoriously bad in Benoni structures so I can't blame Black for wanting to exchange it ASAP.
Finally my King is safe. Somewhat... Black can still use tricks on the a7-g1 diagonal.
This is why Black is happy to exchange the lsb early on his pieces would have a bad case of claustrophobia.
I was just following theory at this point. The aim of this move is to prepare e5.

Black does the same but his goal is the opposite to prevent me from achieving my desired pawn thrust. This move is also safer now that my Rook has left the f-file and f7 isn't under any kind of potential attack.
Gaining the Bishop pair and over-defending e4. The problem is that without the King's Knight the e5 push won't have as much strength.
Forced but Black was more than willing to go through with this exchange. Now he can focus on other things like getting his Q-side pawns rolling and generate pressure there.
If I would have had the time I would have loved to play Bf1 and keep this Bishop covering c4 and d3. It is much more less active of f3.
With my Bishop stranded on f3 Black has a much easier time pushing b5 than in normal lines. I'd say he has equalized here.

I wasn't very happy with this move mainly since there isn't much point behind it. This Bishop is usually kept on c1 when f4 is played at least until White manages to push either e5 or f5. It's kinda loose on e3.

Black is always happy to play this since he can control c4 and d3 now and can start shuffling pieces on the Q-side to attack my pawns. In many a line this pawn is swapped tactically for White's e-pawn giving Black an easy game. Also note that Black hasn't wasted time with a6 which means that there will be fewer pawn exchanges and that that pawn will be slightly less weaker in the endgame.
A pretty meager reply. I've taken care of the direct b4 threat but now c4 will be chronically weak along with all the white squares on my Q-side.
The strategic reply to my last move. Since I don't have any direct control over c4 Black sends his Knight to that square. The only drawback is that e5 has lost of one its protectors.

A flank attack is best countered by a strike in the center. Black allowed e5 but it isn't so bleak he has managed to created enough resources for counterplay. It's worth noting that more slow replies like 16. Qe2 would have quickly lost the initiative since Black would have had time to regain control of e5 and start operations on the Q-side with 16...Nfd7 followed by Rab8 and Nc4 with a very good game.

Remember what I was saying about the Be3? The Nc4 is ideally placed to take care of many problems it defends d6 and e5 it attacks e3 and b2. The alternative variation 16...dxe5 17. fxe5 Rxe5 18. Bxc5 Nfd7 19. Bb4 Qa6 20. b3 would have Black lacking coordination between his forces which are almost cut in half by my d-pawn.
This tactical line wins me two pieces for a Rook and pawn but Black has enough prospects on both flanks to secure a balanced game.
Lines like 17...Bxf6 18. Bd2 Nxb2 19. Ne4 Bd4+ 20. Kh1 Rxe4 21. Bxa5 Nxd1 22. Raxd1 Rxf4 23. Bd2 are needlessly hectic and not very good for Black.

Things have settled and Black has good reasons to be happy with his position. His Rook pair is in complete control of the e-file his King is safer than mine and he still has a menacing Q-side pawn majority. But I still have a few tricks up my sleeve.

Inviting Black to win my Queen for his active Rooks with 21...Re1+ 22. Qxe1 Rxe1+ 23. Rxe1 gxf5 when Black has a lot of pawns and a lonely Queen against my small but more than adequate army. An ending such as this can only be dangerous for Black.
Black replies very coolly ignoring the apparent material gain and consolidates his pawn phalanx. He's not ready to push the pawns and is waiting for me to decide where I place my Queen.

Here I missed my chance to go for the Black squares around the Black King with 21. Qd2! After a possible continuation 21...Qd8 22. Rf1 Kxg7 23. Bg4 R8e5 24. f6! and I'm the one who's on the attack. After my chosen move Black is faced with considerable less problems.
The Queen wasn't doing much on a5 and now that b5 is defended it's time to send her to the other flank.
This wasn't an immediate necessity and could have been postponed for a few more moves. The release of tension only eases Black's choices in what follows.
The f-file is my only source of counterplay but thanks to my hasty pawn exchange Black has a good rebuke to my plan.
An excellent place for the Queen. This simply highlights the strategic drawbacks of playing f4 and h3 early in the game.
Recycling the Knight and sending it for more endeavors on the other flank.
Black is wise to reject exchanges because my King will feel a lot more safe without his pair of Rooks on the board.
Setting up a would-be pin. This also highlights my wrong decision at move 21 on choice of squares for the Queen.
Taking care of all problems on the f-file. Black could even dream of launching a pawn storm on the K-side.
Seeing as things have stalled on the K-side at least for me I turn my attention to the other flank but I don't have high hopes of accomplishing anything without my opponents assistance.
Black can stand the tension no longer and finally gobbles the g-pawn.
A very risky decision but I couldn't stand my passive Knight any longer.
Breaks the pin and aims the Rook at the third rank.
I was going for broke at this point. I really think that with precise play Black could achieve a significant plus from this position.
Very justly played. With my Queen loitering on the edge of the board all Black needs to do is mass his pieces around my King and winning should only be a matter of time.
In for a penny in for a pound.
I wanted at least to exchange these pawns then I could have start to set up some for of defense.
Refusing the exchange and gaining a strong passed pawn. My a-pawn is its white and pale shadow.
I wanted to be able to defend my a-pawn in case Black would decide to attack it but that would mean one less defender on the K-side. Black is very close to winning here.

I don't like this move at all and I can't find a decent reason behind it. I guess Black was concerned about me pushing a5 but that pawn is almost smelling like dead meat. 31...Rb2! would have consolidated Black advantage and all that Black would have to do to win is trade Queens.
Defending the a-pawn.
Doubling on the third rank can be very effective especially in this position when the pawn shelter around my King is as flimsy as a house of straws.
I finally get a route for a decent spot e6 but by now it's too late. Black is active enough to force a perpetual.
Preparing to sacrifice on h3. I can't prevent this without major concessions so I have no choice but to allow it.
At the expense of two heavy pieces my King is bare and defenseless against harassment by the Black Queen.
One last try and hope that Black might play something to give me reason to play on.
Such as 36...Kf6 after which I could have played 37. Qe7+! Kxe7 38. Nxg6+ Kf6 39. Nxh4 Rxh4 40. a5 Ke5 41. a6 Rg4+ 42. Kf2 Rg7 43. Bc6 winning for White. But Black could not be swayed. Draw agreed.

Hi everyone!

I missed a chance late on in the endgame to nail my opponent.  This was by means of a sacrifice namely a backward pawn.  I did not consider the sacrifice because I was worried about giving my opponent a passed pawn so I completely dismissed the idea.  I should have looked a little further into it before doing this as I found out from Coach Ion in a post-match feedback.  I will start the commentary on move 6 since in this Tournament 5. Bxf7+ has been the popular move.
6. Bd5 - another fairly popular move keeping the bishop on the a2-g8 diagonal although Michael does have the option of taking the bishop with his knight.
9. d4 - after a bit of pawn play on both sides I decided to close off the line of black's dsb.
10. ...... bxc6 - this is a recommended move in the gameknot world db - it does disrupt black's queenside pawns to compensate for giving up Fou Leblanc for the knight.
12. ...... Qg6 - out comes the Wicked Witch who is eyeing up the g2 square with evil intent.

15. fxe3 - over the last few moves a plethora of exchanges occurs and both sides now have pawn islands.  My g5 knight is about to disappear and so is one pair of rooks.  I exchange the rooks because I want to cut down on Michael's attacking power on the kingside.

17. Qe1 - my pawn on e3 is very weak so is the one on e4 but never fear Glenda the Defender is here!  I still need to develop my queen knight though.  However black's threats delay this as I must escape Old Matey's shadow after 17. Bh3.
18. Qf2 - now Glenda has two pawns to defend luckily both of these pawns are simultaneously attacked by the Wicked Witch so at least no risk of overload yet.
19. g3 - to defend against the threats on the g column but that lsb on h3 is a real nuisance.
20. ....... Qc5 - black eschews trading queens and there are possible threats of Rg4 to contend with.  Still if Michael does play it then Glenda can go to f3 to defend.
21. Nd2 - at long last!
22. Qxc7+ - Glenda can take a free pawn with check.  I dare not play exd5?? because the Witch can recapture and simultaneously threaten the knight on d2 and mate on g2.
23. Re1 - centralisation and helps defend the e3 pawn.
24. Qf4 - alas Glenda must revert to some defensive work.  Now the h and g pawns are traded off.
26. b3 - this pawn moves to evade capture from the witch and remains on this square for the rest of the game.
28. Re2 - bolstering the second rank.

28. ...... Qa1+ - spent about two or three days trying to ascertain the best place for Henry to go or whether I should block the check with my knight.  I did not like Kh2 because if that black rook could safely land on the h column then that lsb could unleash a devastating discovered check.  If I took the bishop then the Wicked Witch could land on h1 with a really nasty check and then Henry would walk straight into a mating net on the f or g columns.  In the end I decided that f2 was the best place because at least the g3 pawn would be doubly defended and I then found a way to screen off the Wicked Witch's power on my back rank.
30. Re1 - like this.
31. Qd4 - time for some Witch Ejection folks!  I offer a queen trade and my opponent accepts it.
31. Rc1 - necessary to prevent Michael from dominating the c column with his rook to devastating effect.  Black now forces an exchange of rooks.
35. Ke3 - Henry centralises himself and so does the black king.

37. g4?? - this is the move that throws away the win.  I thought that the f3 pawn could be potentially dangerous and my g pawn vulnerable to capture from the black king should Henry try and win the queenside pawns.  However a post match pm from Coach Ion told me I had missed an opportunity by not sacrificing my backward b3 pawn and found a winning line for me viz:- "37.b4 axb4 38.a5 Kd6 39.Kf5 Bh3+ 40.Kxf5 
From here I reckon Black would have had to play very well to have held the draw!"

38. g5 - offering the exchange of pawns and a draw.  I saw that after the trade there was no way Henry could get through to the queenside.  If Henry tried to get through on the bottom half of the board the lsb could cut him off via the b1-h7 diagonal.  If Henry tried to go over the top then the BK could cut him off by moving onto d6 or d7 hence the draw offer.  I could have played on as my opponent's rating was south of mine but as black I got canned by him in the MT and he has been on a roll lately with a draw against a certain Expert.  So I did expect him to find the correct defense.  Ah well c'est la vie.  Time to study pawn breaks methinks.  Anyhow well played Michael.

Hi everyone!

Here is another aspect of my game that I need to improve upon as well as mounting successful mating attacks and spotting those decoys!  It is called Spot the Sacrifice.  I have come across quite a few sacrifices including queen sacrifices when doing the daily puzzles but again I need to develop it in a real game.  In this game I failed to spot an exchange sacrifice and paid the price!  In response to 1. e4 black plays e6 which is the French Defense.

3. ...... exd5 - this pawn trade characterises the Exchange Variation of the French Defense.  It does have the potential to be drawish but it is not always the case.  I thought I would get some nice open free play here.  Well I do but only up to a point.
5. ..... Bd6 - a good square for the bishop both sides have developed pieces and now things start to get a little interesting .....
7. d5 - an attack on the pinned knight on c6 but black can get out of it.
7. ....... a6 - like this.
8. Bxc4 - I now regain my pawn and black takes me out of the database with a queen check along the e column.
10. Kxe2.  I decided to recapture with Henry because I thought about clearing the way for my KR to come to d1 to defend the advanced d5 pawn.

11. Bd3 - Fou Leblanc evades capture by the knight on a5.  This is a good diagonal and I would like him to stay on it but I am worried about the d5 pawn.  Later on it's gonna be the least of my worries!

12. Nc3 - hmm in retrospect maybe instead of following the knights before bishops mantra it would have been better to have played Be3 followed by Nd2 and then my rooks would have a clear communication on the back row and Henry would have been shielded on e2.  Do you the Inquest Jury agree?
14. Kf1.  I did consider Be3 but then I was worried about Ng5 piling up on the pinned prelate.
15. Be2 - to break the pin but alas one step in the wrong direction for yours truly.
16. ....... Bd7.  This bishop looks innocuous on this square.  This is a perfect camouflage for black's future intent though.

18. ...... gxf6 - again I cannot resist to sac B for N in order to do a pawn-busting exercise.  Alas I must now retreat my knight to b1.  If you look at my above note at move 12 I could have avoided having to do this.
20. Nbd2?? - this is the loser.  I did not see the sacrifice coming until it hit me ..... here it comes ......
20. ....... Rxe2!! - ...... here it is!  A real crusher.  Now I must take the rook but that innocuous looking lsb on d7 is gonna deliver a crushing check on b5.

22. ..... Re8+ - another crusher - the only legal move is Ne4 which also gives Henry a flight square.  Black has two pieces for the rook but that is just for starties!  The main course is still to come.
24. ..... Re2+ - nasty nasty this is a real bone in the throat.  Not only can that rook decimate my kingside pawns but a mating net is being woven around Henry.
25. ..... Bf4+ - yup no peace for Henry.
26. ..... Rxf2 - the piggish rook gorges my kingside pawns with impunity.

27. Kc2 - making room for my rooks to move but Nc5 is a death knell because I must now play b3 to give Henry a flight square on b2.  My rook on a1 will fall to a skewer (Be5) next move and so I decided to wave the white flag.  Well played Chris!

This game is a perfect example of how misjudging a position can make you lose a won game. The term "won game" in and by itself is something one needs to be careful with. If you think of a match as having won it already you're prone to make errors which can be costly. In the case of this match it was an innocent looking move and one I didn't put much thought into because I had "won" already that led to my demise.
I'm not too sure why my opponent played a6 considering I had already put my bishop on c4. Maybe he's planning on playing b5 and possibly put his bishop on b7.
This targets the weak f7 pawn.
Strengthening e4 and freeing the dark square bishop.
9. Qa4+ would be answered with 9...Bd7 and my Queen would immediately have to move again. That'd be silly.
Black can't block with knight or bishop because c6 is attacked twice. 10...c6 is possible but weakens Black's queenside pawns. It hangs b6 immediately.
Black chooses to move his king which is definitely a success because he can't castle anymore.

The idea behind 11. c4 is to take back with the c-pawn if Black decides to trade bishops on d5. This way I'd be opening up a file for my rook to attack the enemy king.

Note that 11...c6 is not a threat because of 12. Bxb6+
I'm pushing pawns to pressure the defenses around Black's king.
Having castled my position is now quite a bit better than Black's. I can double up rooks on the c-file and start storming his king.
Black started a counter-attack on my kingside. I didn't think he'd have enough time to become dangerous so I didn't worry about it.
The Black knight is lost. The rook on c8 can't come to the defense because c7 would fall.
Not wanting to lose a tempo I traded down.
Black's two pawns queen and rook are getting menacingly close to my king. But my next move will be Qa5+ and what could Black possibly do about MY oncoming attack right?

28. b5 - in retrospect I consider this a questionable move. Why not play bxc5 instead? The pawn would have a rook behind my queen could come back to b2 in case she needs to defend. But I don't need to defend remember? I'm up a minor piece and a pawn I've chased the Black king across the board and my b-pawn will queen. I've won.
28...g3 so what? Easy to deal with. I'll play f3 lock his queen out and continue pushing my b-pawn. Black is completely lost grasping at straws.
This is the move that cost me the game even though I didn't know it at the time. 29. Rc2 would have been the correct way to defend.

Yeah sure trade down a bit. It'll just make the win easier for me. I'll take back with the king and... oh wait. I can't take back with the king because of 30...Qf4+ which wins my rook. Um okay I didn't see that one when I played 29. f3. But what's the big deal. I'll put the king in the corner and Black won't get anywhere.

Black is getting annoying now. Does he not know that I've already won? Let's see I gotta stop his queen from going to e3 and g1 to defend against mate. Alright no problem. Put the rook on d1. Once my knight moves out of the way the rook will be guarding g1. My rook in turn can be guarded by a knight on c3. And I can always bring back the queen. I'm golden.
Okay I've got to start watching out now. g2 is defended by the knight. If Black's queen goes to e3 I'll play Kxh2. But I really need my queen to defend now. Let's bring her back.

When looking at this position I initially still thought I could defend. I had already won the game earlier so how could I possibly be facing defeat now? But when looking at all my options it started to dawn on me that no matter what I do Black will bust my king wide open and mate me.

The immediate threat is Qg1# of course. And both defensive moves are insufficient.

If 33. Nc2 hxg2+ 34. Kxg2 Rg6+ and 35. Kf1 Rg1# or 35. Kh3 Qh6#
If 33. Kxh2 hxg2+ 34. Kxg2 Rg6+ and Black mates me the same way as above no matter where I go

Why did this happen? Mostly because I was in the wrong state of mind. I didn't take my opponent's threats seriously until it was too late. I learned a lot from this game and hopefully I won't make the same mistakes again.

Hi everyone!

This is the Kings Indian Defense - 4 pawns attack mini-tournament and the third game in my Glenda on h6 theme and this is the happiest outcome of the lot!  Although I do not get to deliver mate a trade off between Glenda and the Wicked Witch of the West results in a decisive gain of material in my favour.  Wanna see how well read on .....
6. Nf3 - again my favoured response after the forced moves.  It adds support to the 4 pawns and develops a piece.
6. ..... c5 - this pawn move tries to undermine the formidable line up of the 4 white pawns on the fourth rank.  To avoid a serious breach in the wall I play d5.
8. ....... Bxe6 - the wall has at last been breached by a pawn trade on e6.  Now I need to develop my back row and I start with Fou Leblanc who moves to d3 to clear the way for kingside castling.
10. f5 - but first I plan to create a breach in my opponent's castled position and this is the start of it.
11. 0-0 - although I do create a balance of king safety and attack on enemy king.

12. Bf4 - Fou Lenoir develops and suddenly threatens Bxd6 winning the exchange + pawn as the d6 pawn is hanging.  Fatcat2 parries the threat with Ne8 - it does make the knight passive though but can I exploit this.  Hmm read on......

15. ...... dxe5 - over the last few moves there has been a plethora of exchanges - now black's dark squared bishop is absent Glenda has a sudden deep desire to leap on her broomstick and get there asap.

16. Nd5 - first though I decided to create an outpost on d5 and threaten to play a move such as f6.  Once Glenda gets onto h6 it could be curtains for the BK if I can only prize that knight out of e8!

16. ...... Nc7 - my opponent kindly offers me a trade off of that defending knight!  I decided to let my opponent trade first because Glenda sneaks onto d2 ready for destination h6.  Notice that after the trade I will take the opportunity to rid myself of my backward pawn on e4 which will open up a line for Fou Leblanc through to h7 to give me more attacking options.
18. ...... Re8 - as you can see that rook is gonna make way for the Wicked Witch to land on f8.  Now Glenda lands on her desired square h6.
19. ...... Qh6 - I did wonder about f6 but then black could play h6 followed by Kh7 and scupper Glenda's plans to land on h6.  So Glenda to h6 it was!

20. Rce1! - I give this move an exclamation mark because I was feeling sooo frustrated at another mating attempt being foiled.  However I suddenly analysed that I could win at least a pawn by a decoy by Qxf8+.  Now take a look at the position after 21. Qxf8+ .....
21. Qxf8+ - Now if Rxf8 you will see that the pawn on e5 is hanging.  Black thinks he can save this pawn however by playing Kxf8 but a trade of pawns on g6 is gonna unsave it!

23. Bxg6 - you wouldn't have thought this move possible a couple of moves before would you?  Look though.  The pawn on f7 is pinned to the BK by my rook on f1.  Therefore Fou Leblanc steals a pawn in broad daylight.  This is the sort of thing that my two buddies Coach Ion and Untateve (Steve) have been inflicting on me.  Well it seems that I may have learned something out of those games because it is my opponent and not me on the receiving end this time!
23. ..... Re7 - defends the f7 pawn but there is a little pawn stab still to come.....

24. d6!  - another decoy this time to lure the black rook away from the defense of the f7 pawn.  If 25. ..... Re6 then 26. Bxf7 attacking the e6 rook and threatening a very nasty discovery on the f column.  If black responds with Rxd6 then 27. Bd5+ any then 28 Rxe5 sees me two clear pawns ahead.  Black did not fancy this and waved the white flag!  I wish I could do this more often!

He decides against the simple Nc3 (which would leave Black down a material point after the dust has settled but of course Black would still have chances to win the game) and throws another piece to the wolves to continue his attack; 22.dxc4 Qxa5 23.Kb2 (White has to defend against Qxa3+) c5 24.Nd3 [Nd5 c6 - woah so doubled pawns DO have a purpose!] Qc3+ 25.Kb1 bxc2+ 26.Qxc2 Qxa3 and Black threatens the crushing Nc3+! winning the queen and this time there doesn't seem to be any way to prevent it. Therefore White would have to after 23...c5 play 24.Kxb3! cxb4 25.axb4 Qe5 and Black's attack is finally repelled

?? White surprises Black once again - though this time it's a pleasant surprise. Black now has a forced mate (my guess is that White saw Black would win at least a piece - the bishop - after White captures the knight so he wanted an extra pawn out of it)

great finish IMHO - Black's pieces have pinned White's king into a corner and have surrounded him! :)

I don't understand why my opponent doesn't launch his pawn to e4 with a classical king pawn opening but all the better for me.
I send out my king pawn- though d5 would have been a better choice.
With fast development of his bishop my opponent puts pressure on the weak f7 pawn though there is not significant pressure as of the moment.
None the less I protect the f7 pawn and develop my knight
Wasted move. Nothing to benefit from it.
I develop my bishop and deny him the right to move his d-pawn in preperation to take out his e-pawn and in the process of pinning his d-pawn I prevent development of his black bishop.
A simple reply to the situation.
I didn't mind moving my bishop away and breaking the pin- the important thing to me was getting my bishop out before I blocked its development with the d-pawn.

Now my opponent is after my bishop and I'm running out of places to put it where it will do good for me. It would have been better to have my bishop on e7 from the beginning instead of fooling with it while letting him create a pawn structure.
I offer the chance to trade bishops in return.
He retreats his bishop.
I do the same with mine and add protection to my e-pawn.
Now my opponent is out to destroy my d-pawn...
...and I defend it.
Now we exchange pawns...
...and I end up with a pawn controlling the center.
Sadly it lacked protection and he snatched it up.
I offer a trade; if he declines then I further protect my e-pawn.
Now he adds pressure to the a8-h1 diagonal but also puts the f7 pawn under significant pressure waiting for me to blunder and move my knight.

Undeterred I add protection to my knight to prevent: 11.Bxc6 bxc6 [or 11... Kf8 and accept the loss of a knight a pawn and the right to castle] 12. Qxc6 leading to a rook-fork and once again the loss of the right to castle.
A move without reason.
I quickly castle to end the immediate pressure on my f7 pawn.
Locks the e-pawns together but does more harm than good blocking of his queen from the a8-h1 diagonal.
The pawn movement also let my knight into a beautiful position not only safe from threats but attacks his queen and forces it back to its d1 post to prevent the dreaded rook fork on c2.
Loss of tempo and lets me pursue other goals without interference from his queen.
I aim to put an unruly grip on the f1 square and confine his king to its square.
My opponent wants to trade away my knight because of its devastating control in his territory.
I see promise in sending my queen to patrol the knight's outpost once the trade is complete; rather than having a pawn there instead doing very little.
The trade...
...and I get my queen in a worthy place forcing him to waste tempo moving his rook or interposing with his knight to prevent the loss of a rook-the latter would be the best move for him.
But no he moves his rook. This fortifies the d-pawn's protection but I had little reason to attack it only to loose my queen.
Here is where I prepared to go in for the kill; and I set the rook out as bait for one possible checkmate [the one that occurred in this game] or to prepare for a more elaborate checkmate.
My opponent took the bait and I am about to set up for a checkmate that is unseen if you are concerned about going for my rook.
I send my queen over and it looks as if it is protecting the rook [even though it is plenty protected] and it seems as this was just a wasted move.
The game is essentially over my opponent took the bait [who cares about losing a rook in order to checkmate?] and I can move in swiftly.
Greed for the rook blinded him from seeing this checkmate.

A Sicilian thematic match Judith Polgar vs Gregory Kaidanov. Annotated by Susan Polgar. http://susanpolgar.blogspot.com/2010/02/match-recap.html

Ini adalah pertandingan dengan tema Pembelaan Sisilia yang digelar di South Carolina Amerika. Judit Polgar dan Gregory Kaidanov dikenal sebagai pakar di pembelaan ini.

Judit surprised Gregory on move 6. She usually plays either the regular Scheveningen with 6.Be2 or the Keres Attack with 6.g4.   Judit mengejutkan Gregory dengan langkah ini biasanya di memakai Gajah e2 atau serangan Keres di bidak g4.

So far all book moves. The basic key ideas in the Sicilian are: White to launch a ferocious attack on the Kingside while Black to launch a counter attack on the Queenside / Center.  Masih dalam langkah teks idenya di Pembelaan Sisilia adalah putih bermain tajam di sayap raja dan hitam di sayap ratu.

This is unusual. 10...Qc7 10...Nxd4 10...Bd7 10...Nd7 are the typical choices. I do not have access to the opening database but I do not recall seeing this move before at this exact order. If Black chooses to play e5 it is usually done right away instead of e6 first then e5.
Now White potentially has a very strong Kingside attack with g4 g5 etc. Black must find a way to create pressure on the Queenside or else Black will have problems.
One option is to launch 13. g4 here.
Now Judit's Knight on c3 is free to go to d5 at the right moment.
Gregory has about 54 minutes Judit has about 1:20 minutes.
White sacrifices a pawn but she has plenty of compensation for it in the form of a Bishop pair a weak d6 pawn space advantage and superior piece placement.
Black could take the pawn of g4 but Gregory decided that it would be too risky to open up the Kingside for Judit.
At this point Judit has about 49 minutes while Gregory has about 39 minutes.
20. h4 is a strong option here.
24. Bxb7 looks good here.
24...Rb8 25. Qxf7 Bf8 26. Bd5 Nxd5 27. Qxd5 Qxd5 28. Rxd5 and White has a big edge in this endgame.
Black is in trouble here.
It looks dangerous but White can comfortably take the Bishop on e7.
This makes things worse as 29. Nxd6 gives White an overwhelming advantage.
31. Rf1 and it is basically over for Black. 31...Rg8 32. Rde1 +-
This also wins comfortably as the endgame is hopeless.

black resign to see inevitable queen+rook combination attack that able to force queen exchange or checkmate black will playing minus two pawns as the ending. 1-0. Hitam menyerah karena kombinasi serangan ratu+benteng putih yang sanggup memaksa pertukaran materi di ujung2 nya putih akan bermain dengan unggul 2 bidak.
14...0-0-0 is another option.
I do not think that this move is necessary at this moment. White should continue to focus on the center and on the Kingside. Every tempo is crucial in the Sicilian Najdorf.
An interesting choice. 16...Bc6 and 16...Rc8 are some other choices.
A possibility for Black if she wants a dynamic game would be 17...d5 18. Bxb6 Qxb6 19. exd5 Nxd5 20. Nce4
So far as expected.
I am not crazy about this move. I prefer 20. Nce4 to maintain pressure on the Kingside. Then the Knight on d2 can go to c4. Now Black has a comfortable position.
21. Qf3 makes sense here. If 21...Bc6 then 22. Be4. If 21...Rc5 then 22. Nc3 +=
The Rook must remain on the c file. Therefore Rc8 Rc6 or Rc7 are all playable. I prefer 22...Rc8.
Now White has a considerable advantage with multiple threats such as Qg3 and f6.
White is breaking through. This will cause the Black King to be in a vulnerable position. 24... gxf6 25. Nd6+ Bxd6 26. Qxf6 +-
Black has serious problems now.
